18:12.660 --> 18:20.040
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. The science fiction of Dean Ing is always
exciting and fast-paced, making it difficult for readers to put his books down.

18:20.340 --> 18:28.500
But his work also has messages to it, some information, some opinions that Ing
wishes to communicate through the entertaining and exciting narrative. Anasazi,

18:28.640 --> 18:35.280
Systemic Shock, and Soft Targets are all good examples of exciting science
fiction novels by Ing, which carry some messages or information along with a

18:35.280 --> 18:41.360
story. Ing bases his writing on ideas, which he's interested in at the time he
writes. He tells us about some of his interests.

19:09.940 --> 19:17.620
There are a couple of themes that have occupied me a lot. I've been talking
about 20 years ago when nobody else cared. Now, a lot of people care. And now

19:17.620 --> 19:28.260
I'm not interested in it much anymore because it's already been, not because of
me, really, but for whatever reason, it has been taken up as an important issue.

19:28.260 --> 19:42.460
The second thing along that line would be survival, not only nuclear survival,
but various other kinds. I write in survival publications. I design backpackers'

19:42.600 --> 19:56.640
wood stoves and all kinds of other gadgetry that would be very useful in
survival contexts. I've had to make my own snowshoes to get out of the High

19:56.640 --> 20:05.040
Sierra one particular summer, which was hardly like a summer at all. It was a
very late spring.

20:08.160 --> 20:16.840
But survival, and particularly the nuclear holocaust survival issue, is one that
I have dealt with for two or three years now.

20:25.900 --> 20:32.260
The End, Ing's latest book, is a good example of his method of writing about his
immediate concerns. It's called Pulling Through, and it's based on the theme of

20:32.260 --> 20:46.860
survival. Pulling Through is a short novel on nuclear survival in the San
Francisco Bay Area. And the short novel is followed in the same book by five

20:46.860 --> 20:57.100
articles, nonfiction articles, detailing some of the gadgetry and techniques
that these people use to stay alive. So that it is not only a fast-paced, short

20:57.100 --> 21:09.260
novel, but it is also a manual of nuclear survival. Ng says he normally tries to
proportion his stories between 90% entertainment and 10% information, but

21:09.260 --> 21:19.460
pulling through is a slight departure from that formula. That is a novel in
which, oh, I must have 20% information in there and only 80% entertainment. But

21:19.460 --> 21:38.500
it is, again, extremely fast-paced. I set a nuclear survival scenario in the
context of a great big overbearing and overwhelming bounty hunter in California.

21:38.960 --> 21:50.380
The kind of guy who, you know, goes around with weapons all the time and has a
fairly high-tech environment. He's a man around whom things just happen, and

21:50.380 --> 22:05.460
they happen fast. But the book is probably 20% information. It's, I guess, the
most thoroughly information-packed novel I've ever written. And the reviews that

22:05.460 --> 22:14.800
are just coming out are very nice reviews. So far, I haven't heard anybody
complain that it's dull. Pulling Through is definitely not a dull novel. It's a

22:14.800 --> 22:21.160
fresh experiment in science fiction and one that will fascinate readers. We hope
Ng continues to include information in his books, along with the narrative.

22:21.420 --> 22:23.580
That's really what science fiction is all about, anyhow.

