23:57.920 --> 23:59.520
And here are your hosts.

24:03.620 --> 24:11.360
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Donald A. Wollheim has been involved in
science fiction for over half a century. His influence has been, and still is,

24:11.440 --> 24:18.800
considerable. He was one of the original fans back in the 30s, and helped start
the famous science fiction group, the Futurians, in New York in the late 1930s.

24:18.920 --> 24:26.140
He's written numerous novels and short stories. He's been an editor of science
fiction for 40 years, and was responsible for the creation of the ace science

24:26.140 --> 24:34.300
fiction line. And today he's head of DAW Science Fiction Books, the publishing
house he founded in 1972. Obviously, Wollheim knows science fiction inside and

24:34.300 --> 24:41.300
out. We asked him to comment on science fiction as a separate category of
literature. Isn't that distinction between science fiction and other fiction,

24:41.480 --> 24:52.780
particularly mainstream, really an artificial one maintained by the publishing
industry? Well, let me put it this way. It is an artificial category. All

24:52.780 --> 25:06.960
literature is literature. But, for the purposes of marketing, it is necessary to
mark out the different genres or categories of what you might call standard

25:06.960 --> 25:17.900
reading. This derives from the fact of the old days of the pulp magazines, when
a magazine was clearly marked a western, or a detective magazine, or a science

25:17.900 --> 25:28.180
fiction magazine. And because it knew that readers who bought that magazine knew
what they were going to get. A mainstream is a very varied product. It consists

25:28.180 --> 25:40.660
of a story of books of modern adventure, books of future life, books of past
life, books of historical, just experimental work. It can be anything. And your

25:40.660 --> 25:50.600
reader of category literature, which is actually, I think, the vast majority,
know what they want. What they want is similar to what they have been reading.

25:50.960 --> 26:02.980
In other words, they don't really want to jump into something which is outside
that which takes them into an escape. They are reading for escape reading. So

26:02.980 --> 26:12.000
you market science fiction because that's what they're looking for. You market a
western if that's what they happen to like. If your western reader picks up

26:12.000 --> 26:22.200
something which is mainstream, he isn't going to like it. It doesn't give him
what he's seeking. The same thing with romance novels. So you have to make it a

26:22.200 --> 26:33.220
category whether the writers like it or not. This is good for marketing. If you
go into any bookshop, a large pay-the-back bookshop, you'll see that they do

26:33.220 --> 26:42.980
this. They put it in separate areas. They market science fiction. They market
romance because they know that people are coming looking for that type of

26:42.980 --> 26:53.460
literature. A science fiction novel published as a mainstream work, unless it's
marvelously good, very well advertised, it's going to be lost. It'll be

26:53.460 --> 27:05.060
forgotten. It won't even be seen. And it certainly won't be reviewed by the
people who read science fiction. They won't tell each other. So for your own

27:05.060 --> 27:11.540
protection, for the author's protection, and for very sound economic reasons,
you do have to list it as a category.

27:19.040 --> 27:25.780
Some people say that science fiction is treated as a second-class form of
literature by critics, that it's unfairly neglected because it is a category

27:25.780 --> 27:35.520
literature. We asked Wolheim's opinion on that notion. Well, I am forced to
agree with those people. The mainstream literature

27:37.940 --> 27:52.300
is, in a sense, regarded as the literature by, let's say, professors of English
and by book critics. And things which are marked in a category style are looked

27:52.300 --> 28:01.960
down upon as hack writing. I see that happen, of course, living in New York. You
see the New York Times book, which was probably one of the most snob organs in

28:01.960 --> 28:10.680
the country, in which they will never review science fiction books if they can
help it. No matter what the critics think, if you like science fiction, you'll

28:10.680 --> 28:13.100
like what Donald A. Wollheim's DAW Books puts out.

